entry.et: Middle English to, from Old English tā; akin to Old High German zēha toe

def.dt: :one of the terminal members of the vertebrate foot
:the fore end of a foot or hoof
:a terminal segment of a limb of an invertebrate
:the forepart of something worn on the foot the toe of a boot
:a part that by its position or form is felt to resemble a toe the toe of Italy: as
:a lateral projection at one end or between the ends of a piece (as a rod or bolt)
:the lowest part (as of an embankment, dam, or cliff)
:toe dance
:alert 1
:facing one another
:to furnish with a toe toe a sock
:to touch, reach, or drive with the toe toe a football
:to drive (as a nail) obliquely
:to clinch or fasten by or with nails or rods so driven
:tiptoe
:to stand, walk, or be placed so that the toes assume an indicated position or direction toe in
:to conform rigorously to a rule or standard
:a piece of material (as leather) covering the toe of a shoe and reinforcing or decorating it
:a dance executed on the tips of the toes by means of a ballet slipper with a reinforced toe
:camber 3
:adjustment of the front wheels of an automotive vehicle so that they are closer together at the front than at the back
:a backward jump in figure skating with a takeoff from the outside edge of one skate followed by a full turn in the air and a landing on the outside edge of the same skate
:slugging it out at or as if at close range a toe–to–toe confrontation over the new policy
:the innermost and largest toe of the foot
